17 materials suggested by education experts, child psychologists, and technology companies
18 that promote child online safety issues.
19 (2) The model programs provided for in this subsection shall include one or more model
20 programs for students in grades six through 12 which:
21 (A) Shall include instruction regarding:
22 (i) The social, emotional, and physical effects of social media on users;
23 (ii) The effects of social media on the mental health of users, particularly teenagers;
24 (iii) The distribution of disinformation and misinformation on social media;
25 (iv) How social media influences thoughts and behaviors;
26 (v) The permanency and risks of sharing materials online;
27 (vi) The dangers of viewing material harmful to minors;
28 (vii) Age verification procedures on websites and social media;
29 (viii) How to maintain personal security and identify cyberbullying, predatory
30 behavior, and human trafficking on the internet and social media; and
31 (vii)(ix) How to report suspicious behavior encountered on the internet and social
32 media to appropriate persons and authorities; and
33 (B) May include information regarding the benefits of social media use, such as
34 supporting career readiness for future academic or employment opportunities, sharing
35 information with familiar family and friends, and safely connecting with other users
36 with similar interests.
37 (3) The Department of Education shall periodically update the model programs provided
38 for in this subsection to reflect changes in internet and social media use, emergent
39 technologies, social and psychological research, and information concerning new threats
40 to teenagers and young adults using social media platforms and other online
41 communication technologies.
42 (4) The Department of Education shall publish on its website information relating to the
43 model programs provided for in this Code section, including recommended curricula and
